                        <p>
                            The stock selection universe is the set of stocks that an investor or a fund manager can choose
                            from when making investment decisions. The stock selection universe can vary depending on the
                            investment objectives, strategies, criteria, and constraints of the investor or the fund manager.
                            For example, some investors may only invest in stocks that meet certain ethical, social, or
                            environmental standards, while others may focus on stocks that have high growth potential,
                            low volatility, or strong dividends. The stock selection universe can also be influenced by
                            external factors, such as market conditions, regulations, availability of data, and liquidity.
                            <br /><br />
                            The stock selection universe is an important concept for portfolio construction and performance
                            evaluation. By defining the stock selection universe, an investor can identify the opportunities
                            and risks in the market, as well as benchmark their performance against a relevant index or
                            peer group. The stock selection universe can also help to diversify the portfolio and reduce
                            the exposure to unsystematic risk. However, the stock selection universe should not be too
                            narrow or too broad, as this may limit the investment options or increase the complexity and
                            cost of managing the portfolio.
                            <br /><br />
                            <b>The S&P 500</b> is a stock market index that tracks the performance of 500 large companies
                            listed on stock exchanges in the United States. It is one of the most widely followed benchmarks
                            for the US economy. But how are companies selected to be part of this index?
                            <br /><br />
                            The selection process is based on a set of criteria that include market capitalization,
                            liquidity, financial viability, sector representation, and public float. The companies must have
                            a market capitalization of at least $13.1 billion, a minimum monthly trading volume of
                            250,000 shares, positive earnings in the most recent four quarters, and at least 50% of their
                            shares available to the public. The companies must also belong to one of the 11 sectors that
                            make up the index, such as technology, health care, or energy.
                            <br /><br />
                            The selection committee consists of analysts and economists from S&P Dow Jones Indices, a division
                            of S&P Global that manages the index. The committee meets on a quarterly basis to review the
                            eligibility of existing and potential constituents, and makes changes as needed to reflect
                            the evolving US market. The changes are usually announced a week before they take effect, and
                            are implemented after the close of trading on the third Friday of March, June, September,
                            and December.
                            <br /><br />
                            <b>The Nasdaq-100</b> is an index that tracks the performance of the 100 largest non-financial companies
                            listed on the Nasdaq stock exchange. The companies are selected based on their market capitalization,
                            which is the total value of their outstanding shares. The index is reviewed and updated quarterly to
                            reflect changes in the market and the eligibility criteria. To be part of the Nasdaq-100, a company
                            must meet certain requirements, such as:
                            <ul>
                                <li>Being listed exclusively on the Nasdaq Global Select Market or the Nasdaq Global Market</li>
                                <li>Having an average daily trading volume of at least 200,000 shares</li>
                                <li>Having a publicly traded security for at least three months</li>
                                <li>Not being involved in bankruptcy proceedings or financial distress</li>
                                <li>Not being a closed-end fund, exchange-traded fund, limited partnership, or royalty trust</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The Nasdaq-100 is a widely followed benchmark that represents some of the most innovative and
                            influential companies in various sectors, such as technology, biotechnology, consumer services, and
                            retail. The index is also used as the basis for several exchange-traded products that allow investors
                            to gain exposure to the Nasdaq-100 market.
                            <br /><br />
                            <b>The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DOW-30)</b> is a stock market index that tracks the performance
                            of 30 large U.S. companies. The companies are selected by a committee of experts from S&P Dow Jones
                            Indices, a joint venture of S&P Global and News Corp. The committee considers factors such as market
                            capitalization, industry representation, trading volume, financial stability, and growth potential.
                            The committee reviews the composition of the index regularly and makes changes as needed to reflect
                            the changing U.S. economy.
                            <br /><br />
                            <b><i>Our investment universe will comprise stocks from the S&para;P-500, NASDAQ-100, and DOW-30 indices.</i></b>
                        </p>
